With the spin-off expected to close as soon as next month, a New York court=
 is
getting an earful. Lionsgate, for its part, says it understands the frustra=
tion of the jilted bondholders, but argues that under the indenture terms, =
they may sue only if they aren=E2=80=99t receiving payments on time. And so=
 far, it seems, they are=E2=80=94though that=E2=80=99s cold comfort when th=
ey say the trading value of their notes is sinking, now that they=E2=80=99r=
e backed by a cable TV relic. (Starz says it=E2=80=99s doing just fine digi=
tally, and apparently the bond prices have actually surged in the past mont=
h, but for
reasons that remain mysterious. Starz has about 20 million subscribers in t=
he U.S., 70 percent via streaming.)

One of the spinoff=E2=80=99s biggest losers is Thebes Offshore Master Fund,=
 a hedge fund operated by Luxor Capital Group. Thebes has argued that Lions=
gate and a select group of advantaged debt holders shouldn=E2=80=99t be abl=
e to trade up at the expense of everyone else, calling it a blatant violati=
on of the bond market=E2=80=99s foundational principle of pari passu=E2=80=
=94equality all around. Why
would any sophisticated financial institution knowingly sign up for such a =
lousy deal? They wouldn=E2=80=99t, of course. Lionsgate, they claim, is tra=
mpling over the indenture=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Csacred rights=E2=80=9D clause,=
 which requires unanimous consent of noteholders before making certain chan=
ges.

Of course, there=E2=80=99s another view: Some of these creditors may be get=
ting exactly what they signed up for. After all, many bought into less rest=
rictive =E2=80=9Ccov-lite=E2=80=9D loans, which have surged in popularity
during the past 15 years, creating loopholes for liability management exerc=
ises and the kind of creditor-on-creditor violence now at play.

Regardless, it=E2=80=99s a mess. And that=E2=80=99s before factoring in the=
 dozens of other entities=E2=80=94BlackRock, California=E2=80=99s public pe=
nsion system, and others=E2=80=94dragged into the litigation simply for vot=
ing their pocketbooks. Fortunately for Lionsgate, the aggrieved bondholders=
 don=E2=80=99t appear eager to actually block the spinoff. What they seem t=
o want is a deal tweak that
sweetens their position. But for now, they=E2=80=99re going to have to figh=
t it out in court.

Deconstruction
Site
--------------

Why is a company worth billions more in pieces than as a whole? It=E2=80=99=
s a perplexing
reality, but let the record show that at the dawn of Trump 2.0=E2=80=94when=
 M&A was supposed to roar back under a friendlier regulatory climate=E2=80=
=94the prevailing trend isn=E2=80=99t consolidation, but rather deconstruct=
ion. Simply put, the market values growth assets (like streaming) more attr=
actively than legacy businesses (like cable TV) that are declining every ye=
ar but still throw off tons of cash.

Comcast and Warner Bros. Discovery, for example, are currently looking to c=
arve out their
linear businesses for this exact reason=E2=80=94a shift that Lionsgate C.F.=
O. Jimmy Barge underscored at last week=E2=80=99s Morgan Stanley TMT confer=
ence. =E2=80=9CThe rationale is maybe even more evident and important than =
ever,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CThis has been all about valuation. We don=
=E2=80=99t feel we are getting [enough] as a combined company.=E2=80=9D

Barge and his colleagues may see the logic in severing the studio from the =
=E2=80=9Cmisunderstood=E2=80=9D Starz=E2=80=94an effort that hinges on shar=
eholder approval, with a vote to be
taken 30 days following whenever the S.E.C. signs off=E2=80=94but getting t=
o this point has been anything but simple. He described a yearslong process=
 hampered by the Covid pandemic and the Hollywood writers strike, further c=
omplicated by Lionsgate C.E.O. Jon Feltheimer=E2=80=99s detour into acquiri=
ng eOne, before ultimately landing on the notion of merging one part of the=
 business with Hollywood investor Harry Sloan=E2=80=99s Screaming Eagle SPA=
C.

Sloan, a former Lionsgate
chairman and current board member, is the architect of these financial gymn=
astics, which will transfer Lionsgate=E2=80=99s 70,000-title library=E2=80=
=94including, somewhat ironically, the buzzy upcoming Seth Rogen Apple TV+ =
series The Studio=E2=80=94to his SPAC. Following the transaction, Lionsgate=
 shareholders will control 87.3 percent of the newly formed entity, with Sc=
reaming Eagle=E2=80=99s owners taking the rest after injecting $350 million=
 in cash.

Naturally, Canada=E2=80=99s public pension fund
and Thebes are challenging the deal, arguing that Screaming Eagle is interf=
ering with their rights under the original indentures. Sloan=E2=80=99s vehi=
cle counters that there=E2=80=99s nothing tortious without an underlying co=
ntract breach=E2=80=94and again, nobody is alleging bondholders aren=E2=80=
=99t getting paid. They also argue that their conduct is excused by legitim=
ate economic justification.

A similar defense is coming from the bondholders participating in the spino=
ff=E2=80=94the lucky bunch being handed new notes backed
by the studio, now paying interest at 6 percent per year instead of the pre=
vious 5.5 percent. In return, these favored creditors permitted Lionsgate t=
o strip key protections under the original indenture, including a requireme=
nt that notes be repurchased upon any =E2=80=9Cchange of control.=E2=80=9D =
Despite allegedly conspiring behind closed doors, this set of bondholders i=
nsist they=E2=80=99re merely innocent bystanders.

Among the chosen few is Liberty 77, the private equity fund run by former m=
ovie producer
Steve Mnuchin, the Secretary of the Treasury under Trump I, who has been ag=
gressively buying up Lionsgate stock and debt for more than 18 months=E2=80=
=94even before the Screaming Eagle deal was announced. His firm, now Lionsg=
ate=E2=80=99s second-largest shareholder with more than 17 percent ownershi=
p, is a co-defendant in the case, and among those pleading for an escape ha=
tch.

Whether this legal skirmish exposes backroom dealmaking remains to be seen.=
 One reason to think Thebes could
advance past dismissal motions? A recent Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals rul=
ing ( http://www.ca5.uscourts.gov/opinions/pub/23/23-20181-CV0.pdf?utm_camp=
aign=3DWhat+I%27m+Hearing%2B+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%283%2F11%2F25%29&utm_content=3D=
What+I%27m+Hearing%2B+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%283%2F11%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_ac=
tion&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) in a case inv=
olving mattress company Serta Simmons. There, appellate judges took issue w=
ith an =E2=80=9Cuptiering=E2=80=9D maneuver that advantaged some creditors =
at the expense of others, finding it violated equal treatment guarantees. T=
he context was different, obviously, as was the jurisdiction, but as one of
the first major rulings on creditor-on-creditor violence, the decision sent=
 ripples through financial and legal circles. Thebes is now citing the Sert=
a ruling in the Lionsgate case, which could be one of the next big decision=
s on this front=E2=80=94perhaps even influencing how other entertainment co=
mpanies finesse their lender negotiations as they navigate a rapidly evolvi=
ng industry.

Of course, the likely real endgame for Lionsgate=E2=80=99s Feltheimer and v=
ice chairman Michael
Burns is to position the company for a sale. Ever since Amazon scooped up M=
GM Studios for $8.5 billion in 2021, Lionsgate has been viewed as the next =
logical indie giant to sell. But I=E2=80=99m told that Lionsgate=E2=80=99s =
team isn=E2=80=99t getting much traction on that front=E2=80=94a potential =
driver behind this latest restructuring. So think of what=E2=80=99s happeni=
ng as being like filing for divorce, hitting the gym, and slimming down bef=
ore looking for a new partner. But which Hollywood companies will survive l=
ong
enough to be along for the ride?

=E2=80=8A

Thanks, Eriq. I=E2=80=99ll be back on Thursday night.
