=3D"margin:0;">With the spin-off expected to close as soon as next month, a=
 New York court is
getting an earful. Lionsgate, for its part, says it understands the frustra=
tion of the jilted bondholders, but argues that under the indenture terms, =
they may sue only if they aren=E2=80=99t receiving payments on time. And so=
 far, it seems, they are=E2=80=94though that=E2=80=99s cold comfort when th=
ey say the trading value of their notes is sinking, now that they=E2=80=99r=
e backed by a cable TV relic. (Starz says it=E2=80=99s doing just fine digi=
tally, and apparently the bond prices have actually surged in the past mont=
h, but for
reasons that remain mysterious. Starz has about 20 million subscribers in t=
he U.S., 70 percent via streaming.)<br/><br/>One of the spinoff=E2=80=99s b=
iggest losers is Thebes Offshore Master Fund, a hedge fund operated by Luxo=
r Capital Group. Thebes has argued that Lionsgate and a select group of adv=
antaged debt holders shouldn=E2=80=99t be able to trade up at the expense o=
f everyone else, calling it a blatant violation of the bond market=E2=80=99=
s foundational principle of <em>pari passu</em>=E2=80=94equality all around=
=2E Why
would any sophisticated financial institution knowingly sign up for such a =
lousy deal? <em>They wouldn=E2=80=99t</em>, of course. Lionsgate, they clai=
m, is trampling over the indenture=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Csacred rights=E2=80=
=9D clause, which requires unanimous consent of noteholders before making c=
ertain changes.<br/><br/>Of course, there=E2=80=99s another view: Some of t=
hese creditors may be getting <em>exactly</em> what they signed up for. Aft=
er all, many bought into less restrictive =E2=80=9Ccov-lite=E2=80=9D loans,=
 which have surged in popularity
during the past 15 years, creating loopholes for liability management exerc=
ises and the kind of creditor-on-creditor violence now at play.<br/><br/>Re=
gardless, it=E2=80=99s a mess. And that=E2=80=99s before factoring in the d=
ozens of other entities=E2=80=94BlackRock, California=E2=80=99s public pens=
ion system, and others=E2=80=94dragged into the litigation simply for votin=
g their pocketbooks. Fortunately for Lionsgate, the aggrieved bondholders d=
on=E2=80=99t appear eager to actually block the spinoff. What they seem to =
want is a deal tweak that
sweetens their position. But for now, they=E2=80=99re going to have to figh=
t it out in court.</p></div>
