bottom:32px;"><div style=3D"color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;In=
ter&#39;,&#39;Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;=
line-height:150%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"m=
argin:0;">Why is a company worth billions more in pieces than as a whole? I=
t=E2=80=99s a perplexing
reality, but let the record show that at the dawn of <strong>Trump</strong>=
 2.0=E2=80=94when M&amp;A was supposed to roar back under a friendlier regu=
latory climate=E2=80=94the prevailing trend isn=E2=80=99t consolidation, bu=
t rather deconstruction. Simply put, the market values growth assets (like =
streaming) more attractively than legacy businesses (like cable TV) that ar=
e declining every year but still throw off tons of cash.<br/><br/>Comcast a=
nd Warner Bros. Discovery, for example, are currently looking to carve out =
their
linear businesses for this exact reason=E2=80=94a shift that Lionsgate C.F.=
O. <strong>Jimmy Barge</strong> underscored at last week=E2=80=99s Morgan S=
tanley TMT conference. =E2=80=9CThe rationale is maybe even more evident an=
d important than ever,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CThis has been all about v=
aluation. We don=E2=80=99t feel we are getting [enough] as a combined compa=
ny.=E2=80=9D<br/><br/>Barge and his colleagues may see the logic in severin=
g the studio from the =E2=80=9Cmisunderstood=E2=80=9D Starz=E2=80=94an effo=
rt that hinges on shareholder approval, with a vote to be
taken 30 days following whenever the S.E.C. signs off=E2=80=94but getting t=
o this point has been anything but simple. He described a yearslong process=
 hampered by the Covid pandemic and the Hollywood writers strike, further c=
omplicated by Lionsgate C.E.O. <strong>Jon Feltheimer</strong>=E2=80=99s de=
tour into acquiring eOne, before ultimately landing on the notion of mergin=
g one part of the business with Hollywood investor <strong>Harry Sloan</str=
ong>=E2=80=99s Screaming Eagle SPAC.<br/><br/>Sloan, a former Lionsgate
chairman and current board member, is the architect of these financial gymn=
astics, which will transfer Lionsgate=E2=80=99s 70,000-title library=E2=80=
=94including, somewhat ironically, the buzzy upcoming <strong>Seth Rogen</s=
trong> Apple TV+ series <em>The Studio</em>=E2=80=94to his SPAC. Following =
the transaction, Lionsgate shareholders will control 87.3 percent of the ne=
wly formed entity, with Screaming Eagle=E2=80=99s owners taking the rest af=
ter injecting $350 million in cash.<br/><br/>Naturally, Canada=E2=80=99s pu=
blic pension fund
and Thebes are challenging the deal, arguing that Screaming Eagle is interf=
ering with their rights under the original indentures. Sloan=E2=80=99s vehi=
cle counters that there=E2=80=99s nothing tortious without an underlying co=
ntract breach=E2=80=94and again, nobody is alleging bondholders aren=E2=80=
=99t getting paid. They also argue that their conduct is excused by legitim=
ate economic justification.<br/><br/>A similar defense is coming from the b=
ondholders participating in the spinoff=E2=80=94the lucky bunch being hande=
d new notes backed
by the studio, now paying interest at 6 percent per year instead of the pre=
vious 5.5 percent. In return, these favored creditors permitted Lionsgate t=
o strip key protections under the original indenture, including a requireme=
nt that notes be repurchased upon any =E2=80=9Cchange of control.=E2=80=9D =
Despite allegedly conspiring behind closed doors, this set of bondholders i=
nsist they=E2=80=99re merely innocent bystanders.<br/><br/>Among the chosen=
 few is Liberty 77, the private equity fund run by former movie producer
<strong>Steve Mnuchin</strong>, the Secretary of the Treasury under Trump I=
, who has been aggressively buying up Lionsgate stock and debt for more tha=
n 18 months=E2=80=94even before the Screaming Eagle deal was announced. His=
 firm, now Lionsgate=E2=80=99s second-largest shareholder with more than 17=
 percent ownership, is a co-defendant in the case, and among those pleading=
 for an escape hatch.<br/><br/>Whether this legal skirmish exposes backroom=
 dealmaking remains to be seen. One reason to think Thebes could
advance past dismissal motions? A recent Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals <a =
href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJ=
LZ0dWaDV5VVduMDYxT2lrcW0yb01tMD0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cDovL3d3dy5jYTUudXNjb3VydH=
MuZ292L29waW5pb25zL3B1Yi8yMy8yMy0yMDE4MS1DVjAucGRmP3V0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1XaGF0K=
0klMjdtK0hlYXJpbmclMkIrLStTVUJTQ1JJQkVSUyslMjgzJTJGMTElMkYyNSUyOVx1MDAyNnV0=
bV9jb250ZW50PVdoYXQrSSUyN20rSGVhcmluZyUyQistK1NVQlNDUklCRVJTKyUyODMlMkYxMSU=
yRjI1JTI5XHUwMDI2dXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbF9hY3Rpb25cdTAwMjZ1dG1fc291cmNlPWN1c3=
RvbWVyLmlvXHUwMDI2dXRtX3Rlcm09ZjZjNjA2MTdkYTQyYWJkMTJhIiwiaW50ZXJuYWwiOiJmN=
mM2MDYxN2RhNDJhYmQxMmEiLCJsaW5rX2lkIjoyMTE3MTgxfQ/9586dd9a2d8e39ee6ec54d809=
4afbbde9c7fb181b9d351aa1a6cd30074c1ffe0" style=3D"text-decoration:underline=
;color:#d40000;">ruling</a> in a case involving mattress company Serta Simm=
ons. There, appellate judges took issue with an =E2=80=9Cuptiering=E2=80=9D=
 maneuver that advantaged some creditors at the expense of others, finding =
it violated equal treatment guarantees. The context was different, obviousl=
y, as was the jurisdiction, but as one of
the first major rulings on creditor-on-creditor violence, the decision sent=
 ripples through financial and legal circles. Thebes is now citing the Sert=
a ruling in the Lionsgate case, which could be one of the next big decision=
s on this front=E2=80=94perhaps even influencing how other entertainment co=
mpanies finesse their lender negotiations as they navigate a rapidly evolvi=
ng industry.<br/><br/>Of course, the likely real endgame for Lionsgate=E2=
=80=99s Feltheimer and vice chairman <strong>Michael
Burns</strong> is to position the company for a sale. Ever since Amazon sco=
oped up MGM Studios for $8.5 billion in 2021, Lionsgate has been viewed as =
the next logical indie giant to sell. But I=E2=80=99m told that Lionsgate=
=E2=80=99s team isn=E2=80=99t getting much traction on that front=E2=80=94a=
 potential driver behind this latest restructuring. So think of what=E2=80=
=99s happening as being like filing for divorce, hitting the gym, and slimm=
ing down before looking for a new partner. But which Hollywood companies wi=
ll survive long
enough to be along for the ride?</p></div>
